<TEXT>
<turn speaker="Lyn_Vaughn" spkrtype="female" startTime="185.0" endTime="204.0">
 Cubans have been waiting for this day for a long time.
<time sec="189.130">
 After months of planning and preparation, Pope John Paul the second will make his first visit to the island nation this afternoon.
<time sec="195.330">
 It is the first pilgrimage ever by a Pope to Cuba.
<time sec="199.648">
 Judy Fortin joins us now from Havana with more. Good morning Judy.
</turn>
<turn speaker="Judy_Fortin" spkrtype="female" startTime="204.0" endTime="249.890">
 Hi, Lyn. The Pope's plane should be landing about four and a half hours from now. He'll begin a hectic five day schedule that includes papal masses in four different cities and meetings, a lot of meetings with church and government officials and, most importantly, ordinary Cuban citizens.
<time sec="221.315">
 [[NS]]
<time sec="223.629">
 Images of Pope John Paul the second are on billboards and posters all over Cuba.
<time sec="228.195">
 It's one of the few ways the Archdiocese of Havana was able to promote the visit.
<time sec="232.415">
 It didn't have permission to advertise on radio or television. 
<time sec="236.175">
 The Cuban government has assured the Vatican there will be no restrictions on the Pope's movement or his ability to give speeches.
<time sec="242.721">
 Cuban Catholics are expecting the Pontiff to preach about the value of religious freedom, something they're just beginning to experience.
</turn>
<turn speaker="spkr_2" spkrtype="male" dialect="non-native" startTime="252.038" endTime="267.597">
 We've seen a true rebirth or a return to the roots and to encounter again a tradition of faith and uh approach to the clo- to the church.
</turn>
<turn speaker="Judy_Fortin" spkrtype="female" startTime="267.597" endTime="273.834">
 Members of the Communist party scoff at suggestions the Pope will try to influence future politics in Cuba.
</turn>
<turn speaker="spkr_3" spkrtype="male" dialect="non-native" startTime="273.834" endTime="279.0">
 I don't think that uh that's in the Pope's mind or the church minds ah at all.
</turn>
<turn speaker="Judy_Fortin" spkrtype="female" startTime="279.0" endTime="306.628">
 Most observers believe President Fidel Castro has carefully calculated the risks, but will gain economically from the visit and will bask in the attention of three thousand visiting journalist. 
<time sec="290.0">
 The US government could stand to lose the most.
<time sec="292.454">
 John Paul is expected to renew his condemnation of the thirty-five year old American economic embargo against Cuba, a policy strongly supported by exiles now living in the United States. Some are returning to their homeland for the historic Papal visit.
</turn>
<turn speaker="spkr_4" spkrtype="female" dialect="non-native" startTime="306.628" endTime="320.010">
 It was a beautiful sight to see my palm trees again.
<time sec="312.987">
 And everybody in the airplane, we were so happy, everybody started just shouting, when we saw land.
</turn>
<turn speaker="Judy_Fortin" spkrtype="female" startTime="320.010" endTime="330.975">
 Fidel Castro will be the first person to greet the Pope when he arrives here in Havana. He'll also have a private meeting with John Paul tomorrow afternoon. 
<time sec="328.131">
 Judy Fortin reporting live in Havana. Lyn, back to you. 
</turn>
<turn speaker="Lyn_Vaughn" spkrtype="female" startTime="330.975" endTime="332.830">
 Thank you very much, Judy. 
</turn>
